Rate Limits¶

Twitter limits the number of requests that you can make to the their API. For documentation, see https://developer.twitter.com/en/docs/twitter-api/rate-limits

The limits are different for different API calls, and if you pay you can get a higher limit.

Write a program that repeatedly makes requests until you hit the rate limit.

Write a comment that explains how you were able to tell that you hit the rate limit, either through something in your program (for example, a try/except) or through something you noticed in an error message.

After you complete this step, you will have to wait about 15 minutes before twitter will let you make any more API calls.

Paging¶

For some requests, like getting the tweets made by an account or the followers of an account, you can't get all the data at once. It comes one "page" at a time; for example, 20 or 200 tweets at a time. In the response data for one page, you will find information that is used to ask for the next page. If you use tweepy Cursors, some of the details of this are handled for you. If not, you have to manage it yourself.

Either way, it's helpful to understand what's going on with paging. The Tweepy documentation has a section on pagination that is worth looking at to get started.

For example, the maximum number of tweets that can be retrieved from a user's timeline in one API call is 200. (Twitter may limit the total number you can request, either through rate limits or otherwise, but you can definitely get more than 200).

Your first task is to write a function that retrieves as many tweets as desired from a user's timeline, even if it's more than 200.

In [3]:
import tweepy
import json
import math

def retrieve_tweets(user_handle, n):
    """
    Retrieve the n most recent tweets by an user_handle
    n may be greater than 200; use paging. If rate limits or paging limits are reached,
      exit gracefully and return the tweets that have been retrieved.
    
    Return a list of tweepy Status objects
    """
    user_feeds = []
    
    ceiling_pages = math.ceil(n/200)
    for tweet in tweepy.Cursor(api.user_timeline, screen_name = user_handle, count = n).pages(ceiling_pages):
        user_feeds.append(tweet)
    
    return user_feeds

import pandas as pd
def create_tweets_dataframe(tweets):
    """
    Create a dataframe from a given sequence of tweets, each represented by one tweepy Status object.
    The dataframe should have the following columns:
        'retweet_count', int
        'created_at', datetime
        'full_text', string
        'favorited', bool
        'retweeted', bool
        'lang', string
        'favorite_count', int
        'hastags', [string]
        'user_mentions', [string]
        'urls', [string]
    """
    df_array = []
    for i in range(len(tweets)): #pages
        for j in range(len(tweets[i])): #tweets within page
            tweet_json = tweets[i][j]._json
            tweet_list = [tweet_json['retweet_count'], tweet_json['created_at'], tweet_json['text'], 
                          tweet_json['favorited'], tweet_json['retweeted'], tweet_json['lang'], tweet_json['favorite_count'],
                          tweet_json['entities']['hashtags'], tweet_json['entities']['user_mentions'], 
                          tweet_json['entities']['urls']]
            df_array.append(tweet_list)
    
    t_df = pd.DataFrame(df_array, columns = ['retweet_count', 'created_at', 'full_text', 'favorited',
                                            'retweeted', 'lang', 'favorite_count', 'hashtags',
                                            'user_mentions', 'urls']) 
    
    t_df['created_at'] =  pd.to_datetime(t_df['created_at'])

    return t_df


tweets = retrieve_tweets('POTUS',10) # use a handle of your interest if you prefer
tweets_df = create_tweets_dataframe(tweets)

def create_weekday_hour_df(tweets_dataframe):
    """
    Create a dataframe that counts the number of tweets per weekday (Mon-Sun) per hour of the day (0-23)
    The dataframe should have the following columns:
        'hour', string (object)
        'weekday', string (object)
        'number of tweets', int
    """

    tweets_dataframe['weekday'] = tweets_dataframe['created_at'].dt.day_name()
    tweets_dataframe['hour'] = tweets_dataframe['created_at'].dt.hour
    tweets_dataframe['sum_by'] = 1

    pivot = pd.pivot_table(tweets_dataframe, index = 'weekday', columns = 'hour', values = 'sum_by', 
                           aggfunc = 'sum', fill_value = 0)
    
    reset_pivot = pivot.reset_index()
    day_hour = pd.melt(reset_pivot, id_vars = ['weekday'])
    
    return day_hour


tweets = retrieve_tweets('AdamSchefter',1000) # use a handle of your interest if you prefer
tweets_df = create_tweets_dataframe(tweets)
weekday_hour_df = create_weekday_hour_df(tweets_df)

def plot_weekday_hour(weekday_hour_df):
    """
    Create a visualization of the number of tweets per weekday (Mon-Sun) 
    per hour of the day (0-23) based on the example above. 
    """
    chart = alt.Chart(weekday_hour_df).mark_rect() \
               .encode(x = 'hour',
                       y = 'weekday',
                       color = 'value')

    display(chart)

Now you'll use the get_place_trends API endpoint to find trending topics in a particular location.

import tweepy

def retrieve_trends(woeid):
    """
    Retrieve the trends available for a given WOEID* using the trends/place endpoint.
    Return an array of trend objects.
    Each trend object should have at least two attributes: a 'name' and a 'tweet_volume'
    Other attributes may be included but are not necessary.
    
    *WOEID (Where On Earth IDentifier): an id that identifies any feature on Earth.
    """
    trends = api.get_place_trends(woeid)

    trends_list = []
    for i in range(len(trends[0]['trends'])):
        trend_list = [trends[0]['trends'][i]['name'], trends[0]['trends'][i]['tweet_volume']]
        trends_list.append(trend_list)
    
    return pd.DataFrame(trends_list, columns = ['trend', 'tweet_volume'])
    
    


retrieve_trends('615702') # Paris

Chart popular locations of followers¶

For the next one, you will need to retrieve a large number of followers for a single user, again dealing with paging, either with tweepy Cursors or directly by requesting one page at a time.

Remember, the documentation resources provided above can help with requesting large amounts of data even when encountering a rate limit. (Note: if you are time constrained, it is acceptabe to simply exit gracefully from the function as long as you are pulling enough data to make a meaningful chart.)

In [12]:
import tweepy
import pandas as pd
import altair as alt
from IPython.display import display

def retrieve_followers(user_handle, n):
    """
    Retrieve the first n followers of the user_hand
    If rate limits or paging limits are reached, exit gracefully and return the tweets that have been retrieved.
    
    Return a list of tweepy User objects
    """
    
    def limit_handled(cursor):
        n=0
        while True:
            print(".", end="")
            try:
                yield cursor.next()
                n += 1
            except:
                print(f"Reached rate limit after {n} iterations")
                break
        return None
            
    followers = []
    
    ceiling_pages = math.ceil(n/200)
    for follower in limit_handled(tweepy.Cursor(api.get_followers, screen_name = 'AdamSchefter', count = n).pages(ceiling_pages)):
        followers.append(follower)
    return followers
            
            
def plot_followers_locations(followers):
    """
    Create a visualization for the locations of followers of the user handle
    Your visualization should look like the examples above.
    
    Note that many users (followers) haven't specified a location. Filter them out or they will
    dominate your bar graph.
    """
    follower_array = []
    for i in range(len(followers)): #pages
         for j in range(len(followers[i])): #followers within page
            follower_json = followers[i][j]._json
            
            if len(follower_json['location']) > 0:
                follower_list = [follower_json['location'], 1]
                follower_array.append(follower_list)
    
    follower_df = pd.DataFrame(follower_array, columns = ['location', 'value']) 
    follower_df.head()

    chart = alt.Chart(follower_df).mark_rect() \
               .encode(x = alt.X('location', sort = '-y'),
                        y = 'record_count:Q') \
               .transform_aggregate(record_count = 'sum(value)', groupby=['location'])
                    
    return chart
